The three componets of every plot: Data - The physical data that underlies the plot. Aesthetics - The aesthetic mappings between the variables in the data and the visual properties. Geoms - A layer which describes observations of the data.

ggplot(mpg, aes(x=displ, y=hwy)) +
  geom_point()

For instance, this plot has: Data - the mpg dataset. Aesthetics - choosing the x and y axis as they are. Layer - points to describe the location of each observation within our mapping.

This plot shows us the car manufacturer for each model name. This is not a useful. A table or list would be better.

Adding attributes in the main plot aes() allows the plot to color/shape/group by value.

ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy, color=class, size=cyl)) + 
  geom_point()

Adding attributes in the geom() will alter that individual layer.

ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) +
  geom_point(color="blue")

You can display categorical data also by facetting. This makes identical plots for each category.

ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~class)

Exercises 1. What happens if you try to facet by a continuous variable like hwy? What about cyl? Whats the key difference?

ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~cty)

The main difference is that it breaks off a new chart for each value of the continuous variable present in the data.

  1. Use facetting to explore the 3-way relationship between fuel economy, engine size, and number of cylinders. How does facetting by number of cylinders change your assessement of the relationship between engine size and fuel economy?
ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~cyl)

Doesnt really change anything.

  1. Read the documentation for facet_wrap(). What arguments can you use to control how many rows and columns appear in the output? nrow, ncol

  2. What does the scales argument to facet_wrap() do? When might you use it? It allows the scales to be variable between the different plots. It would be useful if you have one variable with far different values than the others. If you allow the scales to be dependent on the data, you can get more detail in each plot.

###Time Series

ggplot(economics, aes(date, uempmed)) +
  geom_line()

year = function(x) {
  as.POSIXlt(x)$year + 1900
}
ggplot(economics, aes(unemploy / pop, uempmed)) + 
  geom_path(colour = "grey50") + 
  geom_point(aes(colour = year(date)))

Exercises

  1. Whats the problem with the plot created by ggplot(mpg, aes(cty, hwy)) + geom_point()? Which of the geoms described above is most effective at remedying the problem?
ggplot(mpg, aes(cty, hwy)) +
  geom_point()

Because the values are discrete, there is potential overlap but we cannot see it in this chart.

Here is a better choice.

ggplot(mpg, aes(cty, hwy)) +
  geom_jitter()

  1. One challenge with ggplot(mpg, aes(class, hwy)) + geom_boxplot() is that the ordering of class is alphabetical, which is not terribly useful. How could you change the factor levels to be more informative? Rather than reordering the factor by hand, you can do it automatically based on the data: ggplot(mpg, aes(reorder(class, hwy), hwy)) + geom_boxplot(). What does reorder() do? Read the documentation.
